        // ── Overview (Article) ───────────────────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Financial Reports Overview",
            Slug = "accounting-overview",
            Summary = "What the built-in Financial Reports are, the nine report pages, when these reports apply, and how reconciliation status is shown.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 6,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 1,
            AppRoutes = """["/accounting"]""",
            Tags = """["accounting","finance","reports"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Financial Reports Overview\n\nThe Accounting area is Forge's built-in financial reporting suite. It reads your posted accounting activity and turns it into the nine standard reports an office needs to gauge the health of the business: a Trial Balance, Profit & Loss, Balance Sheet, Cash Flow statement, AR and AP Aging, a GRNI (Goods Received Not Invoiced) report, a Period Close manager, and a Bank Reconciliation worksheet. Every report is read-only. You are viewing what has already posted, not editing transactions here.\n\n### ⚡ When These Reports Apply\n\nThese reports run only when Forge keeps your own books. Forge can either run its own books or hand bookkeeping to an outside accounting provider such as QuickBooks or Xero. You use one or the other, never both. When an outside provider is connected, that provider owns the books, so these reports go quiet. When no outside provider is connected, Forge keeps the books itself and these reports come to life. In short, they do meaningful work only when Forge runs the books and no outside accounting system is in the loop.\n\n### Finding Your Way Around\n\nThe Accounting home page is a grid of tiles, one per report, plus a couple of supporting tools (Bank Statements import and Exports). Click a tile to open that report. Every report opens with a title and subtitle at the top and loads its data as soon as you arrive. Most reports refresh on their own when your accounting activity changes, so you rarely need to reload by hand.\n\n### The Nine Reports\n\n**Trial Balance** — Lists every account with its debit total, credit total, and net balance. A label in the header reads **Balanced** (green) when total debits equal total credits, or **Out of Balance** (red) when they don't. A totals row at the bottom sums the debit and credit columns. This is the foundation report. If the trial balance is out of balance, you can't trust the other statements.\n\n**Profit & Loss** — An income statement showing income lines, then expense lines. Each line lists its account number, account name, and amount. The report subtotals Total Income and Total Expense, then shows **Net Income** at the bottom. If cost of goods sold hasn't posted yet, a note appears at the top so you read the margin with the right expectations.\n\n**Balance Sheet** — Assets, Liabilities, and Equity sections, each line showing account number, name, and amount, with section subtotals. Equity includes a Current Year Earnings line. A header label shows **Balanced** or **Out of Balance**, and the footer ties Total Liabilities and Equity to Total Assets.\n\n**Cash Flow** — A statement of cash flows. It starts from Net Income, applies operating adjustments, then groups Investing and Financing activity, subtotaling the net cash from each. The footer shows the Net Change in Cash and checks it against the actual cash movement. A header label reads **Reconciled** or **Out of Balance**.\n\n**AR Aging** — Money customers owe you, sorted by how overdue it is (the standard buckets are 0-30, 31-60, 61-90, and 91+ days). Each customer is a row with an amount in each bucket plus an Open balance. A totals row sums each bucket and the grand open total. A header label reads **Ties to control** or **Out of Balance**.\n\n**AP Aging** — The mirror image for what you owe vendors: each vendor sorted across the same age buckets with an Open balance, a totals row per bucket, and a **Ties to control** or **Out of Balance** label.\n\n**GRNI** — Goods Received Not Invoiced. It compares what your books hold in the receiving clearing account against goods you've physically received but the vendor hasn't billed yet, and shows the **Variance**. It then breaks the open amount down by purchase order across the age buckets and, when present, lists received items that don't tie to an open purchase order. A header label reads **Reconciled** or **Variance**.\n\n**Period Close** — Manages your accounting periods. Each fiscal year lists its periods, and each period is **Open**, **Soft Closed**, or **Hard Closed**. You can soft-close a period, hard-close it, or close a whole year. A soft close blocks routine posting but you can reopen it later. A hard close locks the period for good.\n\n**Bank Reconciliation** — A worksheet that matches your cash balance to a bank statement. Start by picking a cash account, statement date, and ending balance. Then check off which entries have cleared the bank. The worksheet shows your Book Balance, the Statement Ending Balance, the Cleared total, and the Outstanding total, and tells you the **Difference**. When the difference is zero, the worksheet is **Reconciled** and you can finalize it.\n\n### Reading Reconciliation Status\n\nAlmost every report carries a status label in its header that answers one question: does this report tie out? Green labels (Balanced, Reconciled, Ties to control) mean the report agrees with its control total. Red or amber labels (Out of Balance, Variance, Difference) mean something doesn't reconcile and needs a look before you rely on the numbers. The label is the fastest way to sanity-check a report at a glance.\n\n### When to Use Financial Reports\n\n- When you need a snapshot of the business — Profit & Loss for the period, Balance Sheet for the date\n- When confirming the books tie out — Trial Balance balanced, AR and AP aging tying to their control accounts\n- When chasing money — AR Aging for who owes you, AP Aging for what you owe\n- When closing a period — soft-close during review, hard-close to lock it down\n- When reconciling cash — matching your entries to the bank statement on the Bank Reconciliation worksheet\n- When checking received-not-invoiced exposure — the GRNI variance and purchase-order breakdown","sections":[]}"""
        });

