            ContentJson = """{"passingScore":80,"questionsPerQuiz":8,"shuffleOptions":true,"showExplanationsAfterSubmit":true,"questions":[{"id":"ac1","text":"When do the built-in Financial Reports actually do meaningful work?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Whenever an outside accounting provider like QuickBooks is connected"},{"id":"b","text":"When Forge keeps your own books — no outside accounting provider is connected and the built-in books are switched on","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Only after every fiscal period has been hard-closed"},{"id":"d","text":"Only when both an outside provider AND Forge's books are enabled at the same time"}],"explanation":"These reports run only when Forge keeps your own books. You use Forge's books or an outside provider, never both. When a provider is connected it owns the books and these reports go quiet. They come to life only when Forge keeps the books and no outside system is in the loop."},{"id":"ac2","text":"The Trial Balance header shows a red 'Out of Balance' label. What does that tell you?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The report failed to load and should be refreshed"},{"id":"b","text":"Total debits do not equal total credits, so you can't trust the other statements until it's fixed","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"A fiscal period needs to be hard-closed before the report will balance"},{"id":"d","text":"There are received items that don't tie to a purchase order"}],"explanation":"The Trial Balance label reads 'Balanced' (green) when total debits equal total credits and 'Out of Balance' (red) when they don't. It's the foundation report. If the trial balance is out of balance, the Profit & Loss, Balance Sheet, and Cash Flow built on top of it can't be relied on."},{"id":"ac3","text":"What are the standard age buckets used by the AR Aging and AP Aging reports?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"0-7, 8-14, 15-30, and 31+ days"},{"id":"b","text":"Current, Past Due, and Written Off"},{"id":"c","text":"0-30, 31-60, 61-90, and 91+ days","isCorrect":true},{"id":"d","text":"Monthly columns for the trailing twelve months"}],"explanation":"Both aging reports use the standard 0-30, 31-60, 61-90, and 91+ day buckets, shown as columns with an Open balance for each customer or vendor. The totals row sums each bucket and the grand open total."},{"id":"ac4","text":"On the Profit & Loss report, what does the margin note at the top mean?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The report is out of balance"},{"id":"b","text":"Cost of goods sold hasn't posted yet, so the margin you're reading is incomplete","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"An outside accounting provider is connected and the report is read-only"},{"id":"d","text":"The fiscal period is hard-closed and the figures are final"}],"explanation":"When cost of goods sold hasn't posted, the Profit & Loss shows a note so you read Net Income with the right expectations. The margin is incomplete until cost of goods sold lands. Once it posts, the note goes away."},{"id":"ac5","text":"In Period Close, what is the difference between a Soft Closed and a Hard Closed period?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"They are the same — both lock the period for good"},{"id":"b","text":"Soft Closed blocks routine posting but can be reopened; Hard Closed locks the period for good","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Soft Closed locks the period; Hard Closed only warns when posting"},{"id":"d","text":"Soft Closed applies to a period; Hard Closed applies to an entire fiscal year"}],"explanation":"A Soft Closed period (amber label) blocks routine posting but you can reopen it. A Hard Closed period (muted label) is locked for good and shows 'Locked' with no further actions. From an Open period you can soft-close or hard-close; from Soft Closed you can reopen or hard-close."},{"id":"ac6","text":"On the Bank Reconciliation worksheet, you check off several lines as cleared. What happens?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Each check saves right away"},{"id":"b","text":"Checking a line only stages the change — nothing is saved until you click 'Update cleared'","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The worksheet finalizes automatically once any line is cleared"},{"id":"d","text":"The lines are deleted from the reconciliation"}],"explanation":"Checking a line only stages the change and shows a count of unsaved changes. Nothing is saved until you click 'Update cleared'. You can finalize only when the worksheet is reconciled and there are no unsaved cleared changes."},{"id":"ac7","text":"The GRNI report shows a non-zero Variance. What is it comparing?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Total debits against total credits across the whole books"},{"id":"b","text":"What your books hold in the receiving clearing account against goods received but not yet billed by the vendor","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Your cash balance against the bank statement ending balance"},{"id":"d","text":"Total Assets against Total Liabilities and Equity"}],"explanation":"GRNI (Goods Received Not Invoiced) checks the clearing account. It compares what your books hold there against the open amount your operations report, and shows the Variance. A 'Reconciled' label means they agree; a 'Variance' label means they don't. The report also breaks the open amount down by purchase order and flags received items with no purchase order."},{"id":"ac8","text":"You need to see which customers owe you money and how overdue each balance is. Which report do you open?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"AP Aging"},{"id":"b","text":"AR Aging","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Cash Flow"},{"id":"d","text":"Trial Balance"}],"explanation":"AR Aging shows who owes you, with each customer's open balance spread across the 0-30, 31-60, 61-90, and 91+ day buckets. AP Aging is the mirror image for what you owe vendors. Cash Flow and Trial Balance don't break balances down by customer or vendor."}]}"""
