            AppRoutes = """["/accounting/exports"]""",
            Tags = """["accounting","finance","exports","quickbooks","csv"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Exporting for Your Accountant / QuickBooks\n\nMost shops that keep their books in Forge still have an outside accountant who prepares the tax return and reviews the year. The **Exports** page (a tile on the Accounting home page) is how you hand that person the data they need, without giving them a login and without making QuickBooks the source of record. The page has two halves: CSV downloads, always available, and an optional one-way send to QuickBooks Online that appears only when your install has turned it on.\n\n### The Two Ways to Share\n\n**CSV downloads (always on).** Three buttons under the *CSV Export* heading each download a file your accountant can open in Excel or import into their own software:\n\n- **Trial Balance CSV** — every account with its debit, credit, and net for the date range you picked. This is the most-requested file, the snapshot an accountant reconciles against.\n- **GL Detail CSV** — the line-by-line detail behind the trial balance, so the accountant can trace any balance down to the individual entries.\n- **Journal Summary CSV** — the period's activity rolled up to one net figure per account (the same data the QuickBooks send uses). Use it when the accountant just wants the period's movement, not every line.\n\nAll three use the **date range** you set at the top of the page. It defaults to month-to-date and offers two shortcuts, *This Month* and *Last 30 Days*, or you can pick your own start and end. Click a download button and the file saves. Only one download runs at a time.\n\n**Send to QuickBooks Online (optional, off by default).** When your install turns on the QuickBooks send *and* QuickBooks is connected, a second section appears below the CSV buttons. It does one thing: it posts the period's per-account net as a **single balanced journal entry** into QuickBooks Online. This is a one-way send. QuickBooks is never read back, and nothing it holds overwrites your Forge books. If the send is off (the default), you simply won't see this section, and CSV is your way to share.\n\n### Matching Your Accounts to QuickBooks\n\nQuickBooks has its own list of accounts that won't match your Forge account numbers. So before you can send, each Forge account with activity has to be matched to the right QuickBooks account. The matching editor is a table: one row per account, showing the Forge account number and name, with a field to enter the matching QuickBooks account and a save icon to store it. A matched row also shows a delete icon to clear it. You set this up once, and the matches stick for future sends.\n\n### Sending to QuickBooks\n\n1. Set the **date range** to the period you're delivering (for example, last month or the quarter).\n2. Make sure every account with activity in that range is matched to a **QuickBooks account**.\n3. Click **Send to QuickBooks**. A confirmation restates the dates, since this writes into QuickBooks, so it asks before it acts.\n4. On success you get a confirmation with the QuickBooks reference for the journal entry it created.\n\n### When a Send Is Refused\n\nThe send refuses rather than deliver incomplete or duplicate data, and tells you why on screen:\n\n- **An account with a balance isn't matched.** Match it to a QuickBooks account and send again. The summary has to be complete and balanced before it can land.\n- **The range overlaps a period you already sent.** This guard stops you from posting the same activity into QuickBooks twice. You'd only override it on purpose.\n\n### The Big Picture\n\nForge keeps the books; the accountant reviews them. CSV is the universal, no-setup way to deliver the trial balance and its detail to anyone. The QuickBooks send is a convenience for shops whose accountant prefers the numbers to land in QuickBooks directly as one tidy journal entry per period, but it's strictly one-way reporting, never a sync. Whichever path you use, the data lives in Forge first. The export is a copy going out, not a source coming in.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Exporting — Guided Tour (Walkthrough) ────────────────────────
