            AppRoutes = """["/accounting/bank-statements"]""",
            Tags = """["accounting","finance","bank","reconciliation","import"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Importing & Matching Bank Statements\n\nReconciling cash by hand means eyeballing a paper statement against your entries line by line. The **Bank Statements** page (a tile on the Accounting home page) automates the tedious part. You upload the file your bank gives you, Forge matches each bank line to one of your entries where it can, and you confirm the matches. Confirmed lines then feed straight into the Bank Reconciliation worksheet, so the two screens work together: import here, finalize on Bank Reconciliation.\n\n### Pick the Cash Account, Then Import\n\nEvery statement belongs to one cash (bank) account, so the first control on the page is a **Cash Account** picker. Pick the account the statement is for before you import. If you click Import without choosing one, Forge reminds you. Then click the **Import** button at the top and choose your file. Forge accepts the formats banks actually hand out: **OFX, QFX, CSV, and TXT**. OFX and QFX are the download formats from your bank; CSV and TXT cover plain exports.\n\n### What Happens on Import\n\nTwo things run automatically the moment the file lands:\n\n- **Duplicate detection.** Each transaction carries a unique ID from your bank. Forge uses it to skip repeats, so re-importing the same statement — or an overlapping one — won't create double lines. The result tells you how many lines were imported and how many were skipped as duplicates.\n- **Auto-match.** Forge immediately tries to match each imported bank line to one of your open entries on that cash account, by amount and by how close the dates are. The result tells you how many matches it suggested.\n\nAfter import, the new statement appears in the **imports list**, one row per file, showing the file name, format, line count, duplicate count, a summary of how many lines are Suggested, Unmatched, and Confirmed, and the import date. Click a row to open its lines below.\n\n### Reading the Lines and Their Match Status\n\nEach imported line shows its posted date, description, amount (money going out is shown in a warning color), a **status**, and — when matched — the entry it matched to. Status is the heart of the screen:\n\n- **Unmatched** (amber) — Forge couldn't find one of your entries for this bank line. It needs your attention.\n- **Suggested** (blue) — Forge proposed a match. Review it, then confirm or ignore it.\n- **Confirmed** (green) — you accepted the match. The line is settled and will clear on the reconciliation.\n- **Ignored** (muted) — you set this line aside (say, a bank fee you'll handle separately) so it stops asking for a match.\n\n### Working the Queue\n\nEach line offers a few actions, and which ones show depend on its status:\n\n- On a **Suggested** line: **Confirm** accepts the proposed match, or **Ignore** sets it aside.\n- On an **Unmatched** line: **Ignore** to park it.\n- On a **Confirmed** or **Ignored** line: **Unmatch** reverses your decision and sends the line back to the queue.\n\nIf you've added new entries since importing, click **Re-run auto-match** (above the lines) to have Forge take another pass at the still-unmatched lines and suggest fresh matches.\n\n### How It Feeds Reconciliation\n\nConfirming a match is your way of saying the bank settled that entry. That's exactly what the **Bank Reconciliation** worksheet needs: the entries you confirm here are the ones that show as cleared there. So the flow is: import the statement and confirm matches on this page, then open Bank Reconciliation, where the cleared total reflects your confirmations and the worksheet tells you whether you tie out. Import is the data-entry step; Bank Reconciliation is where you finalize.","sections":[]}"""
