            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Bank-Statement Import Edge Cases\n\nThe Bank Statements page has several behaviors worth knowing for the trickier cases.\n\n- **Accepted formats:** OFX, QFX, CSV, and TXT. OFX and QFX are the download formats from your bank; CSV and TXT are plain exports.\n- **Cash account is required first.** The page opens with a Cash Account picker, set to your first cash account. If you import without one chosen, Forge reminds you to pick one.\n- **Duplicate handling.** Each transaction carries a unique ID from your bank, and the import uses it to skip repeats, so re-importing the same or an overlapping statement passes over the ones already loaded. The result tells you how many lines were imported, how many were duplicates, and how many matches were suggested.\n- **Auto-match on import.** Auto-match runs the moment you import, comparing each bank line to your open entries on that cash account by amount and by how close the dates are. **Re-run auto-match** (above the lines) takes another pass at only the still-unmatched lines. Use it after you add new entries.\n- **How a line's status moves:** Unmatched (amber) needs attention; Suggested (blue) waits for you to Confirm or Ignore; Confirmed (green) is settled and will clear on Bank Reconciliation; Ignored (muted) is parked. **Unmatch** sends a Confirmed or Ignored line back to the queue.\n- **Confirming settles, it doesn't post.** Confirming a match doesn't record any accounting entry. It's your way of saying the bank settled that entry. Confirmed entries are exactly the lines that show as cleared on the Bank Reconciliation worksheet; you finalize there, not here.\n\n## Export Date Shortcuts and Refused Sends\n\nThe Exports page delivers your books to an accountant. Two ways to share, one date range.\n\n- **Date range** defaults to month-to-date. It offers the shortcuts **This Month** and **Last 30 Days**, or set your own. The start and end constrain each other.\n- **Three always-on CSVs:** Trial Balance, GL Detail, and Journal Summary. No setup, no connection. Only one download runs at a time, and the file saves with the name the server gives it.\n- **The QuickBooks send is optional.** The \"Send to QuickBooks\" section shows only when your install turns it on and QuickBooks is connected. It posts the period's per-account net as **one balanced journal entry** — strictly one-way; QuickBooks is never read back.\n- **Match your accounts first.** For the send, you match each Forge account with activity to a QuickBooks account: one row per account, enter the QuickBooks account, then save it or clear it. Rows you haven't matched stay empty.\n- **When a send is refused,** it refused rather than deliver incomplete or duplicate data: either an account with a balance still isn't matched, or the range overlaps a period you already sent. Forge shows the reason on screen. Match the account and try again, or deliberately override to re-send an overlapping range.\n\n## Aging Buckets\n\nBoth aging reports group balances by age, and the buckets aren't fixed to four columns.\n\n- The standard buckets are **0-30, 31-60, 61-90, and 91+** days, but the report can show **up to six**. The buckets and their labels come from the report, so they adapt to how your install is set up. The top bucket is open-ended (everything older).\n- One row per customer (for AR) or vendor (for AP), plus an **Open** balance. A totals row sums each bucket and the grand open total. The first column stays put as you scroll sideways.\n- The header label reads **Ties to control** (green) when the report agrees with its control account, or **Out of Balance** (red).\n\n## Table Power Features\n\nThe aging reports, Trial Balance, the GRNI purchase-order breakdown, Period Close, and Bank Statements all use the shared table, which brings its full set of power-user features.\n\n- **Sort** by clicking a column header; sort by **more than one column** with Shift+click.\n- **Filter each column** (text, number, date, or a pick-list) from the column's filter popover.\n- **Manage columns** from the gear icon: show or hide, reorder, resize, and reset widths. Right-click a header for the same menu plus clear-sort and clear-filter.\n- **Your layout sticks.** Column layout and sort survive a reload, saved to your preferences.\n- **The first column stays put** so the customer, vendor, or account name stays visible while the other columns scroll sideways.\n- The statement-style reports (Profit & Loss, Balance Sheet, Cash Flow, and the GRNI summary) don't use this table on purpose. They read as grouped statements with subtotals, so they have no per-column filtering or column manager.\n\n## Multiple Sets of Books (Planned)\n\nForge is built to hold more than one set of books, but the suite ships with a single set today.\n\n- Every report runs against one set of books today. There's no picker to switch sets yet.\n- A **picker arrives with support for multiple sets of books**. Until then, all reports, exports, bank import, and reconciliation work against that single set.\n- This is groundwork for later, not a switch you can flip now. Nothing exposes a second set of books today, but the plumbing is in place so the picker can be added later without disruption.\n","sections":[]}"""
